Definition

Hallucination occurs when an LLM generates incorrect or fabricated information while presenting it confidently as if it were true.

Real-world Analogy

Imagine a student who doesn't know the answer in an exam but confidently writes something that sounds convincing.

Salesforce Example

If asked about a Salesforce feature that doesn't exist, the model may invent APIs, objects, or functionality instead of admitting it doesn't know.

Interview Question

Q: What causes hallucinations in Large Language Models, and how can they be reduced?